            <sourceDesc>
                <msDesc>
                  <msIdentifier>
                    <repository ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/INS0809MJR">John Rylands Library</repository>
                    <collection>Ethiopic Manuscripts</collection>
                    <idno facs="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/iiif/MS-ETHIOPIC-00027" corresp="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/iiif/MS-ETHIOPIC-00027">Ethiopic MS 27</idno>
                  </msIdentifier>
                  <msContents>
                    <summary><seg>A copy of the 'Arbā'tu wangēl (Four Gospels). The manuscript opens with prefatory matter written by a later hand that containins a general introduction,
                      the epistle of Eusebius to Carpianus, and the Eusebian canons.</seg></summary>
                    <msItem xml:id="ms_i1">
                      <title xml:lang="gez-Latn-x-lc">'Arbā'tu wangēl. Four Gospels</title>
                      <textLang mainLang="gez">Ge'ez</textLang>
                    </msItem>
                    <msItem xml:id="ms_i1.1">
                      <locus from="5r" to="11r">5r-11r</locus>
                      <title xml:lang="eng">Prefatory Matter on the Gospels</title>
                    </msItem>
                    <msItem xml:id="ms_i1.2">
                      <locus from="12r" to="86v">12r-86v</locus>
                      <title xml:lang="gez">ማቴዎስ. Matthew</title>
                    </msItem>
                    <msItem xml:id="ms_i1.3">
                      <locus from="88r" to="135v">88r-135v</locus>
                      <title xml:lang="gez">ማርቆስ.  Mark</title>
                    </msItem>
                    <msItem xml:id="ms_i1.4">
                      <locus from="136r" to="219r">12r-86v</locus>
                      <title xml:lang="gez">ሉቃስ. Luke</title>
                    </msItem>
                    <msItem xml:id="ms_i1.5">
                      <locus from="220r" to="272v">220r-272v</locus>
                      <title xml:lang="gez">ዮሐንስ. John</title>
                    </msItem>
                  </msContents>
                  <physDesc>
                    <objectDesc form="Codex">
                      <supportDesc material="parchment">
                        <support>
                          <material key="parchment">Parchment</material> book block.</support>
                        <extent>275 folios (iv+275): <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                          <height>405</height>
                          <width>345</width>
                        </dimensions>
                          <dimensions type="outer" unit="mm">
                            <height>414</height>
                            <width>372</width>
                            <depth>120</depth>
                          </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation>
                          <p>Modern pencil foliation in Arabic numerals on the upper right corner of each recto folio.</p>
                        </foliation>
                        <collation><p>The quires of the main manuscript are partly numbered, separated in the cases of Matthew, Mark, and Luke. Quire 9 in Matthew is unnumbered; quires 12-14 in
                          Mark are unnumbered. John contains four unnumbered quires.</p></collation>
                        <condition><p>Folio <locus from="4r" to="4r">4r</locus>: The right-hand portion of the leaf is missing; the leaf is only 23 cm wide.</p></condition>
                      </supportDesc>
                      <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="2 3" writtenLines="20 40">
                          <p>Folios <locus from="5r" to="11r">5r-11r</locus>: Three columns, 40 lines per leaf.</p>
                          <p>Folios <locus from="12r" to="172v">12r-172v</locus>:Two columns, 20 lines per leaf.</p>
                          <p>Folios have been pricked and scored to assist in writing.</p>
                        </layout>
                      </layoutDesc>
                    </objectDesc>
                    <handDesc hands="4">
                      <handNote xml:id="h1" scope="major" script="Ethiopic" medium="ink">
                        <p>Written in a <term ana="#">Ge'ez</term> script, in black and red ink.</p></handNote>
                      <handNote xml:id="h2" scope="minor" script="Ethiopic" medium="ink">
                        <p>Folios <locus from="5r" to="11r">5r-11r</locus> contain writing from a second hand.</p></handNote>
                      <handNote xml:id="h3" scope="minor" script="Ethiopic" medium="ink">
                        <p>Folio <locus from="11v" to="11v">11v</locus> contains a list written by a third hand.</p></handNote>
                      <handNote xml:id="h4" scope="minor" script="Ethiopic" medium="ink">
                        <p>Folio <locus from="273v" to="273v">273v</locus> contains lists written by a fourth hand.</p>
                      </handNote>
                    </handDesc>
                    <decoDesc>
                      <decoNote xml:id="d1"><p>Illuminated heading at the beginning of each Gospel: <locus from="12r" to="12r">12r</locus> (Matthew), <locus from="88r" to="88r">88r</locus> (Mark), <locus from="136r" to="136r">136r</locus> (Luke), and <locus from="220r" to="220r">220r</locus> (John).</p></decoNote>
                    </decoDesc>
                    <additions>
                      <p>Folio <locus from="2r" to="2r">2r</locus>: Three lines of writing in black and red ink at the top of the first of three columns; the leaf is from another manuscript.</p>
                      <p>Colour threads were tied onto the foredge of the leaf; only two are preserved (ff. <locus from="16r" to="16v">16</locus> and <locus from="102r" to="102v">102</locus>).</p>
                      <p>On <locus from="11v" to="11v">11v</locus> and <locus from="273v" to="273v">273v</locus>: lists of däbtäras of different rankings for the church (?) of Fänsa: (የፈንፃ ፡
                        ደብተሮች ።) The የግራ ፡ and የቀኝ ፡ ደብተሮች ፡ as well as the የግራ ፡, የቀኝ ፡ መሮች ፡ and several other functions are indicated for the respective months: on 11v for Mäskäräm (መስከረም),
                        Ḫǝdar (ሕዳር), Ṭaḥṣaṣ (ታሕሳስ), Ṭǝr (ጥር), and Yäkatit (የካቲት); on f. 273v, another list for Mäskärām (መስከረም). Beginning (11v):</p>
                      <p>መራኅያን ፡ ዘየመን ፡ ዘመስከረም ። አዘጅ ፡ ቴዎዶጦስ ።</p>
                      <p>ሊቀ ፡ መዘምር ፡ ወልደ ፡ ሃይማኖት ። አባ ፡ አምኃ ።</p>
                      <p>ቀዳስያን ፡ ዘየማን ። ሰላመ ፡ ሥላሴ ፡</p>
                      <p>አባ ፡ ፊልጶስ ። ዓርከ ፡ መርዓዊና ፡ አባ ፡ አካሉና ፡ ቄስ ፡ አፄ ፡ አዕይንቴ ።</p>
                      <p>ባላምባራስ ፡ ወልደ ፡ ሥላሴ ።</p>
                      <p>አስላፊ ፡ ገለስዮስ ።</p>
                      <p>ቤት ፡ ጠባቂ ፡ እዱግ ፡ አቡቂር ፡</p>
                      <p>የግራ ፡ መሮች ፡፡</p>
                      <p>መልአከ ፡ ፀሐይ ፡ ቴዎድሮስ ። ፀዳሉ ።</p>
                    </additions>
                    <bindingDesc>
                      <binding contemporary="true" notBefore="1700" notAfter="1799">
                        <decoNote xml:id="b1">Ethiopic binding. Full leather bound with wooden boards and large leather turn ins. Covering leather in two pieces, sewn together in a vertical line down the
                          centre of the spine and decorated with blind tooling. Splits in outer leather on spine along both board joints. Boards lined on the inner side with flowered silk.
                          Additional square strip of leather at the head and tail attached to the spine and 1cm of inner front and back board as a sort of spine lining - endbands are tied
                          down through this secondary leather. Brown leather split braid endbands, sewn and glued to leather spine lining squares - tie downs are not visible on the outer
                          cover. Unsupported sewing at 6 stations (three even pairs of sewing stations). The sewing is laced into the boards as an integral part of the sewing process and is
                          done in separate pairs with each pair sewn using a different thread..</decoNote>
                        <decoNote xml:id="b2">Central text panel is noticeably whiter and smoother than the surrounding parchment suggesting it was prepared for writing differently, perhaps polished.</decoNote>
                        <decoNote xml:id="b3">Inserted silk bookmark in the book block - not attached.</decoNote>
                        
                      </binding>
                    </bindingDesc>
                  </physDesc>
                  <history>
                    <origin>
                      <origDate calendar="gregorian" notBefore="1700" notAfter="1800" cert="high">18th century</origDate>
                      <origPlace><country ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000489">Ethiopia</country></origPlace></origin>
                    <provenance>
                      <p>An inscription on <locus from="12r" to="12r">12r</locus> indicates the manuscript belonged to the Church of the Savior of the World located at <placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC0000">Āmba Maryam</placeName> (i.e. Magdala): ወንጌል ፡ ዘቅዱስ ፡ መድኃኔ ፡ ዓለም ።.</p></provenance>
                    <provenance><p>Owned by <name role="fmo"><persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS0000">Näbiye Le'ul</persName></name>, <name role="fmo"><persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS0000">Wäldä Giyorgis</persName></name>,
                      and <name role="fmo"><persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS0000">Wälättä Kidan</persName></name>.</p></provenance>
                    <provenance><p><name type="person" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420" role="fmo"><persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS0000">James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847-1913)</persName>
                      </name>. The <locus from="1r" to="1r">first folio</locus> bears the armorial
                      bookplate (Ex Libris) identifying the codex as having once been part of the Bibliotheca Lindesiana, the private library of the Lindsay family, Earls of Crawford and
                      Balcarres | <locus from="1r" to="1r">Armorial bookplate (Ex Libris)</locus>: ARMS: Quarterly, 1st and 4th, Gules a fess chequy Argent and Azure; 2nd and
                      3rd, Or a lion rampant Gules, debruised of a ribbon in bend Sable. CREST: a swan’s head, neck, and wings proper, issuing from an antique ducal coronet Or. SUPPORTERS:
                      two lions, rampant guardant Gules. MOTTO in Latin: Endure fort (Endure bravely) | Bibliotheca Lindesiana | pencilled: 5/G. Pencilled on left inner upper cover: Ethiopic MSS | No 27.</p>
                    </provenance>
                    <provenance><p>Purchased by <name type="person" role="dnr"><persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS0000">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName></name> in <date calendar="gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847-1913).</p></provenance>
                    <acquisition><p>Bequeathed by Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908) in <date calendar="gregorian" when="1908">1908</date> to <name type="institution" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/152274029" role="his"><orgName type="display">The John Rylands Library</orgName></name>.</p>
                    </acquisition>
                  </history>
                  
